@NODE "BLANKNATIVE" "The monitor remains blank on native modes"

@{b}I use a graphics card without a video pass-through, but my monitor
remains blank after booting to the workbench@{ub}

By default, P96 attempts to redirect the native video modes to the
native video output if no P96 mode is found. However, as there is no
monitor switch on your card, it cannot do that. Thus, the video is at
this point still coming out of the native Amiga video out.

To resolve the problem, connect your monitor back to the native
output, then setup the P96 modes with "P96Mode".

Alternatively, add the following ToolType to the monitor icon in
DEVS:Monitors:

FakeNativeModes=YES

Then reboot. This will redirect the native video output to the
P96 output, and will give you a workbench that is good enough to
setup P96 completely. It will only give you a single 640x480 screen
mode, so it is not a replacement of a mode promotion utility.


@{b}I use a graphics card with a video pass-through, but my monitor
remains blank after booting to the workbench@{ub}

Maybe your monitor is not able to display native Amiga video signals,
which use a horizontal frequency of 15Khz. Most modern monitors can no
longer display such signals and then remain blank.

To resolve the issue, first connect an older monitor or a TV to the
native Amiga video output, and setup P96 by running the "P6Mode"
program.

Alternatively, add the following ToolType to the monitor icon of your board
in DEVS:Monitors:

FakeNativeModes=YES

Then reboot. This will give you a 640x480 video mode on your graphics
card to which the workbench is redirected.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "NOMODES" "Cannot select RTG graphics modes in mode requesters"

@{b}I cannot select any RTG graphics modes in the screen mode requester@{ub}

Ensure that the necessary system components are installed. In
particular, each graphics card requires two components in
LIBS:Picasso96, namely a "card" driver, and a "chip" driver. The
former addresses all card specific functions such as driving a switch
between the RTG output and the native output, the latter handles the
lower-level functions such as programming the graphics mode into the
chip and driving an on-board blitter. The installer script should
have placed the necessary components there, but if you use a graphics
card not natively supported by this distribution, contact your vendor
on installation details.

Ensure that a monitor file is installed in DEVS:Monitors. The name of
the file is typically identical to that of the graphics card. If you
use a custom Startup-Sequence, ensure that this file is loaded.

Ensure that you have already selected graphics modes for your
board. For that, open the "Prefs" drawer on the workbench, and there
double-click on the "P96Mode" icon. The program may warn you that no
modes are found.

If so, move the mouse under the left-hand "open box"
item, keep the mouse button pressed, and drag a new setting into the
"Settings" list, which should then appear there in the list of
available settings. If not already selected, single click on this
setting. Then use "Attach Settings to" menu, and select the board to
which this setting should be applied.

P96Mode will then create some default modes according to the VESA
standards. They may probably not yet ideal for your card and may
require further adjustments.

Further instructions on how to use this program:

@{"P96Mode" link "PICASSO96MODE"}

@ENDNODE

@NODE "NODRAG" "I cannot drag screens"

@{b}Version 3.0 of P96 was announced to offer screen dragging, but I still
cannot drag screens@{ub}

Screen dragging is limited by the abilities of the VGA graphics chips
used in RTG graphics boards, and available memory on the board. If you
cannot drag a screen, then one of the following reasons may be
responsible for it:

The two screens simply do not fit into the graphics card memory. For
example:

An 8 bit 1280x1024 screen with 256 colors already requires more than
1MB of memory. A graphics card with 2MB memory on board can hence
simply not hold two of them in memory. If you switch screens, P96 will
copy the screen memory to standard CPU memory, and then copy the
screen data of the screen made visible to the board. Obviously, this
cannot work if the two screens together require more memory than
available on the board.

The two screens have different depth. Unfortunately, most VGA chips
cannot switch the depth within an active display. Hence, a 256 color
screen may not be able to share the display with a 16-bit high-color
screen, and a 24 bit true-color screen may not be able to share the
display with a high-color screen either. A 4-plane planar screen can
neither share the screen with a 2-plane planar screen.

Due to another limitation of the VGA chips, an autoscroll screen
cannot be the lower (frontmost) screen of two screen displayed
simulatenously.  VGA can only pan the upper screen.

Due to limitations in the VGA memory, planar screen modes typically
only have 256K or even 128K of display memory available, regardless of
how much memory is installed on the board. Thus, even if the memory
required by two planar screens is smaller than the installed memory,
it may still happen that screen dragging does not work because the
total amount of memory is above 256K.

VGA chips can neither switch the width of screens sharing the same
display. That is, if two screens of different widths are about to
share the same display, P96 needs to allocate board memory of a width
that is the maximum width of the two screens. If one of the screens is
an autoscroll screen, chances are high that the total memory required
to align the two widths to the maximum exceeds the available board
memory.

VGA chips can display at most two screens at once. Hence, the upper
screen on a shared display can never be dragged to make room for a
third screen.

A native Amiga screen cannot share the display with a RTG screen
because the RTG/native screen switch cannot be triggered in the middle
of the display. You can, however, run a screen-promotion utility to
redirect a native screen to a similar RTG screen.

Last but not least, the VGA chip on your RTG board may simply not
support screen dragging, or its driver has not been updated to support
screen dragging. The 3DLabsPermedia2 chip and boards based on it such
as the CVisionPPC/BVisionPPC does not support screen dragging as its
hardware lacks the necessary hardware support.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "FALSECOLORS" "False colors while dragging screens"

@{b}If I drag screens, the upper screen shows false colors@{ub}

Most VGA chips do not include a copper and hence cannot switch the
palette mid- screen. Instead, the palette is always shared between two
screens. If the two screens use a different palette, the colors for
the topmost screen will be off.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "WRONGRESOLUTION" "Wrong resolution of upper screen"

@{b}When dragging screens, the upper screen is rendered in a wrong resolution@{ub}

VGA chips cannot switch resolutions within a display. Hence, the upper
screen is always shown in the same mode as the lower screen. You may
pan this screen with the mouse, though, if its width does not fit the
native display width.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "DRAGDELAY" "Delays when dragging screens"

@{b}When I drag screens, the computer seems to pause for a while with a black
display@{ub}

Due to limitations of the VGA display model, P96 has to re-organize
memory to allow display sharing. This reorganization may take a
while. During this reorganization, the screen is blanked. Every
following screen dragging operation on the same pair of screens will,
however, perform immediately.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "NOUAEGFX" "UAEGfx driver is missing"

@{b}The UAEGfx driver is no longer included in the distribution@{ub}

This driver is copyrighted by a third party and hence cannot be
included for legal reasons. Actually, the latest versions of UAE
do not require a driver, and just a properly adjusted monitor
icon. For that, install P96 without selecting a graphics card.
P96 will then install a monitor of type "Generic" into
DEVS:Monitors. Then edit the tool types and insert there the
following tool type:

BOARDTYPE=uaegfx

Then reboot.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "NOPTRSWITCH" "Mouse pointer disappears on UAE after screen switch"

@{b}When using the UAEGfx driver on an old Linux UAE or eUAE version,
the mouse pointer disappears when switching screens@{ub}

This is a bug in the UAEGfx driver that trashes one CPU register.
Unfortunately, the driver is copyrighted by a third party and a fix
cannot be distributed for legal reasons. Switch to a newer version of
UAE and its driver.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "NOFASTLAYERS" "The fastlayers.library is missing"

@{b}What happened to the fastlayers.library? Why is this no longer included?@{ub}

Because it is no longer needed. Os 3.1.4 contains a newer version of
the layers.library that is already faster to begin with. If you do not
own Os 3.1.4, you find a V45 version of the layers.library in the
Aminet. Follow the installation procedures of this library in the
Aminet archive.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "MOUSECOLOR" "Wrong mouse pointer color"

@{b}One of the mouse pointer colors look wrong@{ub}

This is due to limitations of many VGA chipsets used in Amiga graphic
cards. Typical VGA sprites have only two colors, the third color is
formed by inversion of the background.

You can either try to redesign your mouse pointer with the pointer
preferences to avoid the third color, or you can switch to a software
rendered sprite. For that, add

SOFTSPRITE=Yes

as tool type to the monitor icon of your graphics board.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "DOUBLEPTR" "Doubled mouse pointer at top of screen while dragging"

@{b}When dragging screens, the mouse pointer is oddly doubled on top of the
screen@{ub}

This happens on graphic cards based on Cirrus chipsets, and the issue
is cased by a hardware bug of these cards. The sprite is erroneously
re-triggered after the screen split location, causing the doubled
sprite. P96 tries to work around this issue as much as possible, but
cannot do if the screens overlap close to the top edge of the monitor.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "SLOWSCROLL" "Scrolling is slow"

@{b}Why is scrolling so slow on my board?@{ub}

There could be multiple reasons. First, some graphic boards simply do
not offer a blitter, and then the CPU has to move all the data. This
can be quite slow, in particular on screens with many colors. You can
then only reduce the screen dimensions, or reduce the number of colors.

The second reason may be that the program running on the screen
installed a bitplane mask, attempting to scroll only one of the Amiga
bitplanes. However, graphic cards do not operate on bitplanes, and
then P96 has to emulate the mask, which is slow. To avoid this problem,
add the tooltype

IGNOREMASK=Yes

into the monitor icon of your graphic board. While P96 will then
ignore the mask, it may draw graphics differently than intended, so
use with care, and revert the change if the side effects are worse
than the cure.

The reason may also be that the blitter on the board may be simply
disabled. For this, check whether the tool types of the monitor icon
of the affected board include the line

NOBLITTER=Yes

If so, just remove this line, save the changes and reboot.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "MOUSEFLICKER" "Flickering mouse pointer"

@{b}My mouse pointer flickers badly@{ub}

This happens if the mouse pointer is drawn by software instead of
using a hardware sprite. Then P96 has to remove the mouse pointer
every time a program attempts to update the screen close to the
pointer, and then needs to redraw the pointer afterwards. This causes
the flicker.

If the board offers a hardware sprite, you may enable it by editing
the tool types of the monitor icon of your board and include the line

SOFTSPRITE=No

or remove the line "SOFTSPRITE=Yes".

However, not all boards offer a hardware sprite, and in such a case,
there is unfortunately nothing P96 can do to avoid the problem.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "COLOREDGE" "Strange colors on right screen edge"

@{b}Strange colors appear on the right edge when panning@{ub}

If you see colorful bars on the right edge of 8 bit (256 color chunky)
or 4 bit (16 color planar) screens when panning autoscroll screens,
here is a workaround for Cirrus-based boards:

Edit the tool types of the monitor icon of your board, and add
there the tooltype

BORDERBLANK=Yes

save the changes and reboot. This is a hardware defect of early Cirrus
chips such as the GD542x or GD5434 present on the GVP Spectrum, Picasso II,
Piccolo or PiccoloSD64. The above chip family does not disable display DMA
correctly at the right display edge when panning, and reads instead false
colors. Enabling border blanking masks this problem.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "NOLEFTBLANK" "Left screen border not blanked"

@{b}The left border on the Retina card is not blanked@{ub}

On 8-bit and 4-bit color modes, the leftmost border of any mode of the
Retina graphics card appears in the background color rather than
black, regardless of the BORDERBLANK tooltype of the monitor
icon. This is a workaround for an off-by-one error in the NCR77C22E+
chip which requires an offset between the start of the picture and the
end of the border-blanking period. There is unfortunately nothing that
can be done to avoid this problem.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "RETINABUG" "True color modes look wrong on Retina"

@{b}True-color modes show wrong colors on the Retina card@{ub}

The NCR77C22E+ chip or the AT&T RAMDAC on the Retina card seem to
misbehave in some situations or for some revisions, causing
misalignment between the channels. To work around this problem, add
the tooltype

TRUECOLORKULDGE=Yes

to the icon of the Retina graphics card, save the changes and
reboot. This should hopefully avoid the problem.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "MERLIN" "Instabilities of the Merlin Card"

@{b}Instabilities of the Merlin Card@{ub}

Development of the Merlin card was never finished, and the card was
sold before all issues have been identified. While its manufacturer
still offers a hardware fix, even this fix does not work on all board
revisions in all circumstances. Thus, please do not expect that
software will solve this problem, and it might be worth investing into
a better card. You may try the following workarounds as last resort:

Set the tooltype

INTERRUPT=No

to disable hardware interrupts. You may also try the tooltype

NOBLITTER=Yes

to disable all blitter operations of the card. This will slow down
most graphics operations, but may avoid one cause of instability.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "RETINAINIT" "The Retina, GVP EGS 110 or A2410 cards do not initialize"

@{b}The Retina, GVP EGS 110 or A2410 cards do not initialize@{ub}

If you see an error message when loading the Retina, GVP EGS 110 or
A2410 card driver, despite having installed proper drivers, please
ensure that you also installed the mmu.library.

For the Retina card, the library is required to create the illusion of
a linear frame buffer as the NCR chip otherwise only offers segmented
memory access P96 cannot handle.

A similar issue exists for the GVP EGS 110 card which is not
auto-configuring and hence requires manual intervention of the
mmu.library to make it visible to the CPU.

The A2410 is very special by not making its framebuffer available to
the 68K. Instead, P96 maintains a shadow framebuffer into which it
renders its graphics. The MMU is here required to identify all changed
display regions and copy them back to the card.


You find the mmu.library on Aminet:

http://aminet.net/util/libs/MMULib.lha

Please follow the installation procedures in this archive.

Note that your system needs a working MMU for the Retina and A2410
drivers. The Retina and A2410 card drivers will thus not work on a
68EC030, 68EC040 or 68EC060. 68020-based systems will require a 68851
MMU, a 68020 alone is not sufficient.

The GVP EGS 110 driver does not require a MMU, but if one is present,
the MMU tables need to be adjusted through the mmu.library to allow
the driver to detect it.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "RETINADEBUG" "Debugger pops up when starting the Retina"

@{b}Debugger messages when starting the Retina card@{ub}

If you see warnings on access errors while starting up the Retina
card, or while operating it, update or configure your development
tools. The access errors are generated by the CPU attempting to access
currently non-visible memory segments of the NCR77C22E+ chip, and they
are usually handled by the P96 chip driver.

To avoid these problems, make sure that you use most recent debugging
tools that are aware of the mmu.library and its exception handling
strategy. In particular, you should upgrade the "Enforcer" to
"MuForce" which will not report access errors the P96 driver already
detected and handled.

Also, if you are using the COP debugger, you should switch it to
passing access errors over to the mmu.library. The command "ENVI.H"
does that.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "VISIONANOPIC" "No picture on Visiona or GVP EGS 110 card"

@{b}My monitor does not accept the output of the Visiona or GVP EGS
110 card and remains black@{ub}

The Visiona and GVP EGS 110 cards create a video signal corresponding
to TV standards, and does not follow VGA standards. Regular VGA
monitors may not be able to interpret the signal generated by this
card.

As a resort, you may try the following:

- Connect the monitor with a VGA cable that cuts the VSYNC signal
off, and also

- Set the "SYNC" tool type of the Visiona icon to "tessellated".

Mode configuration for the Visiona and GVP 110 EGS cards may be rough
as the parameter interpretation is not quite equivalent to that of
regular VGA-based designs. You find in the archive in

DEVS/Picasso96Settings.Visiona

settings that may be used as basis for your modes.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "NOVISSCROLL" "No autoscroll screens on Visiona or GVP EGS 110 card"

@{b}AutoScroll screens do not open on Visiona@{ub}

Unfortunately, the INMOS chip on the Visiona card does not support
panning (scrolling) for chunky screen modes wider than 2048 pixels, or
true color screen modes wider than 512 pixels. Also, the size of
bitmap that is panned on the mode cannot be wider than 2048 or 512
pixels. That is, an autoscroll screen of 2000x1000 pixels on a
1024x768 screen mode will work for a chunky screen, but a 1000x1000
screen on a 800x600 true color mode will not.

Similar problems exist for the GVP EGS 110 card. While the hardware
supports panning for screens as wide as 8192 chunky pixels or 2048
true color pixels, but such screens require huge amounts of RAM that
are typically not available. Panning may only work if the video RAM
on the card is maxed out to 8MB.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "LEFTPIXMISSING" "Left or right columns missing on Visiona and GVP EGS 110 cards"

@{b}Left pixel rows missing on Visiona@{ub}

The INMOS chip on the Visiona card has an erratum that prevents it
from displaying the leftmost pixel column correctly in true color (24
bit) modes. P96 can partially compensate this defect by also shifting
pixels when writing data into the frame buffer. By default, data is
shifted by 4 pixels, but this may not be the ideal choice for all
cards. You can adjust the offset by adding the tool type

TRUECOLORPIXSHIFT=<value>

to the Visiona monitor icon, and experimenting with the value. This
should be a number between 0 and 6.

Unfortunately, this defect has another consequence for true-color
autoscroll screens where, depending on the value of the above
tooltype, either left or the right columns of true color autoscroll
screens may be missing.


@{b}Right pixels missing on GVP EGS 110@{ub}

A similar issue exists on the GVP EGS 110 card which may make the
rightmost column invisible on true color screens. To avoid this
problem, prefer the RGBA video mode which should not be affected
by this problem.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "VISIONATOP" "Erratic pixels on first screen line of Visiona or GVP EGS 110 output"

@{b}Erratic pixels on topmost line on Visiona and GVP EGS 110 screens@{ub}

The INMOS chips on the Visiona and GVP EGS 110 card have an issue that
prevents it from showing correct pixels in the topmost (first) line of
the video buffer. Here, pixels may be weirdly permuted as some pixels
are displaced to the right of their intended position. There is
unfortunately no workaround P96 can offer. The defect does not impact
the output much on intuition screens as the first line is typically
part of the screen dragbar which appears in one solid color.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "VISIONACOLORS" "Spurious wrong colors on Visiona and GVP EGS 110 card"

@{b}Sometimes screens on Visona or GVP EGS 110 cards show wrong colors@{ub}

If you switch screens, or adjust the palette, it sometimes happens
that the screen colors are not loaded correctly. This is unfortunately
due to a hardware issue of the cards which does not tolerate palette
register writes during the active screen area. P96 tries its best to
work around the problem and attempts to synchronize palette reloading
to the vertical blanking area, but cannot ensure proper timing under
all circumstances.

To reduce the chances of false colors, try the following:

- Reduce the CPU workload during the vertical blank. In particular,
background music is often played in the vertical blank interrupt, and
thus reduces the time available for the palette change.

- Modify the P96 mode settings for the affected display modes, in
particular enlarge the frame size and/or the size of the vertical sync
while keeping the vertical resolution constant. This will enlarge the
vertical blanking time and by that also the time available for P96 to
load the palette to the chip.

- Screen colors may also change while drawing on the screen as the INMOS
chip tends to forget its palette registers especially when rendering to
its video RAM. This situation can be somewhat avoided by reducing the
pixel clock, i.e. lowering the refresh rates of the screen.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "MISSINGMODES" "Missing screen modes for emulators"

@{b}Why do I not see video mode XXX which I need for a specific emulator@{ub}

P96 shows by default only the essential modes, but excludes modes that
offer the same color resolution, but in a different bit layout. You
may enable additional modes in the following way:

Open a shell, then enter the following line:

echo "All" >ENVARC:Picasso96/ShowModes

Then reboot the machine. This will enable all screen modes the chip
supports, even those that are non-essential. For example, the
Permedia2 chip supports 6 hi-color modes, and 4 true-color modes.
There is probably the right mode waiting for you in this list.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "FUSIONCOLORS" "False colors in Fusion emulator"

@{b}I'm using the Fusion Mac emulator, but true color screens on the
emulated Mac do not work correctly and show false colors.@{ub}
   
Unfortunately, Fusion has a bug in its screen rendering code as it
interprets the depth information in the "Display Info Database"
incorrectly. The data base indicates the number of bits defining the
possible number of color shades a mode supports, but Fusion expects
instead the number of bits per pixel. Those two numbers disagree if
the mode includes an alpha channel or a stencil bit.  To work around
this defect, proceed as follows:

Open a shell, then enter the following line:

echo "Yes" >ENVARC:Picasso96/DepthIncludesAlpha

Then reboot the machine. This will add the alpha channel bits and the
stencil bit in the computation of the depth of all P96 screen modes,
thus delivering the number of bits per pixel Fusion expects, rather
than the number of colors available.

Note that this workaround may also affect other programs using the
same database, and filling the database incorrectly may limit or
affect their functionality. It is advisable NOT to enable the above
workaround unless absolutely necessary.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "PPCCOLORS" "Warp3D shows false colors on CVisonPPC"

@{b}I'm using Warp3D with the CVisionPPC, but the colors in 3D animations
are all wrong, or does not work at all.@{ub}

Due to a hardware limitation, Warp3D cannot support all possible color
formats in all cases. This is partially due to a hardware limitation
of the 3DLabs Permedia2 chip which Warp3D is unfortunately not aware
of, and partially that Warp3D cannot handle some mode switches of the
chip correctly.

To work around this issue, several tricks need to be used:

First, you need to select the proper screen modes. For access all
possible screen modes, open a shell, then enter the following line:

echo "All" >ENVARC:Picasso96/ShowModes

Then reboot the machine, and select the proper screen mode according
to the following instructions:

If you want to run a Warp3D program on the workbench, use either
the 16 bit mode without "BGR" or "PC" in the name, or the 32 bit
"BGRA" mode.

If you want to run a Warp3D program on its own screen, however,
use either an 8 bit mode, a 16 bit PC mode (note the "PC"), or
the 32 bit "BGRA" as workbench screen mode.

Note in particular that depending on whether you want to run an
application on the workbench or on a separate screen, the "allowable"
Hi-Color screen mode is different. "BGRA" is always working.

Note also that iComp cannot guarantee that Warp3D works correctly.
This is a third-party product that is no longer maintained. In
particular, iComp cannot offer services or bug fixes for this
product. Use at your own risk.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "SLOW3D" "Warp3D is slow on the CVisionPPC"

@{b}I'm using Warp3D with the CVisionPPC, but the animations are
all slow@{ub}

It may be necessary to update the firmware of the CVisionPPC to the
latest, albeit non-official release, namely to 44.71. This also adds
autoconfig nodes to the system such that the board hardware is also
mapped correctly.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "WRONGVOODOOCOLORS" "Corrupted icon colors on the Voodoo card"

@{b}I'm using a Voodoo card with the Elbox driver, but all my
icons show wrong colors@{ub}

The Voodoo driver does not interpret minterms correctly if a masked
blit is accelerated with the onboard blitter. This is a known defect
of the driver. In particular, blitting through a mask requires a
minterm of 0xe0 instead of the "cookie cut" minterm 0xc0, please see
the documentation of BltMaskBitMapRastPort().


To work around this issue, set the tool type


NOMASKEDBLITS=YES


in the monitor icon of the Voodoo card. This will disable hardware
acceleration for masked blits, avoiding the problem.

@ENDNODE

@NODE "MISSINGHARDWARE" "Missing driver for hardware"

@{b}Why don't you support hardware XYZ...@{ub}

Probably because we don't have access to it, or probably because there
is no documentation on it how we could support it.

@ENDNODE

